
[1]plunder

   PLUN'DER, v.t.

   1. To pillage; to spoil; to strip; to take the goods of an enemy by
   open force. Nebuchadnezzar plundered the temple of the Jews.

   2. To take by pillage or open force. The enemy plundered all the goods
   they found. We say, he plundered the tent, or he plundered the goods of
   the tent. The first is the proper use of the word.

   3. To rob, as a thief; to take from; to strip; as, the thief plundered
   the house; the robber plundered a man of his money and watch; pirates
   plunder ships and men.

   PLUN'DER, n. That which is taken from an enemy by force; pillage; prey;
                                   spoil.

   1. That which is taken by theft, robbery or fraud.
